<font color="#FF0000">1ST DAY, FIRST SIGNS OF GUILT</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 25 10:05:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
ON the Way to the land of No Postage Stamps, from Okinawa;<br><br>
CHAPTER  TWO<br>
DaNang, South Viet Nam<br>
1300 Hours, Friday, June 16th, 1967<br><br>
       It started to rain shortly before our departure and what had looked like ordinary brown dirt turned into slippery, slimy, yellow mud. Since we were lined up alphabetically once again, I was among the first men in formation and was about to board the plane when the NCO (Non Commissioned Officer) in charge of the flight assigned me and five others the task of loading our seabags aboard the plane.  As we loaded the duffel bags into the rear of the plane, the rain started to fall in torrents.  In a matter of minutes our heavy cotton utilities were dripping wet and our shiny black leather boots covered with fine gooey yellow mud. When we finished, I was the last to board the plane. As I walked through the door, the stewardess reached behind me and closed it tight. It was exactly 1300 hours and immediately the plane began to taxi along the runway. <br>
This time there were no in-flight movies, no stereo earphones, and even the stewardesses were older and grouchy.  Like a dispiriting soul, gloom walked up and down the airplane's aisles, a solemn silence echoed throughout the plane. We sat there in secret wonderings, staring at each other and at nothing in particular.  No one uttered a word. We were on our way to Viet Nam and war and there was no turning back. <br>
In less than two hours, the hushed silence was broken by someone who mentioned that we had escorts. We looked out the planes windows and saw two camouflaged phantom jets at our wings escorting us into South Viet Nam's air space.  Minutes later far below us, the coast of South Viet Nam came into view.  As we began our approach into DaNang, below us hundreds of small and medium size sampans listed off shore. Further in other small craft were traveling into or coming out of the mouth of two large rivers. A range of  mountains seemed to be converging into the South China Sea.  The land further away and toward the city lay low. A beautiful mountain range off in the far distance provided a beautiful and spectacular green colored background. As I was taking in the country's beauty, the noise from our jet escorts brought my mind back to our destination. The jets backed off, banked left and were gone. The plane turned right dropped suddenly and touched down smoothly. We taxied to the other end of the airport near some long wooden barracks and began to disembark . <br>
Our utilities were still soaking wet when we touched down at the air base in DaNang, but when we walked off the plane by stepping onto old style portable metal stairs, they dried instantly in the sizzling hot Vietnamese sun.  The air was hot and humid with a mixed smell of dead fish, burning incense and rotten vegetables. An acidly smell lingered in the air, making it hard to breathe. The air first burned the lining of your nose, then its toxic, sulfuric odor worked its way down into your lungs. It was the smell of human waste, jet fuel, and dead fish. It was the smell of confusion, fear, death and decay mixed with hopes and dreams.  <br>
Since those of us who had loaded the sea bags on board were seated up front, the five of us were once again assigned to the unloading of the duffle bags. When we finished we were re-assigned to the loading of seabags for those going home. I remember the heaviness of our seabags compared to those we loaded on board. Our olive-drab seabags were large, bulky clean and crisp.  Those we loaded on board for the Marines going home were scrawny, faded, dirty dusty, and torn.  I wondered if mine would be just as faded and worn after my tour of duty or if the seabag would be sent back alone.<br>
Before us, was a large wooden hanger with a wide opened entrance. The missing front doors, evidence that the facility was always open. We all picked up our seabags and went through the barracks entrance.  Inside, two aisles of long wooden benches were lined up under the hanger's tin metal roof. As we walked in, we were greeted by a squeaky loud speaker. <br>
&quot;Welcome to the Republic of Viet Nam.  Please report to the front of the depot and convert all US Currency into MPC (Military Payment Certificates).&quot; The MPC we received in exchange looked like Monopoly play money. <br>
We were told to stay near the transit barrack and wait for further instructions. All around us, Marines in various stages of transit lounged around the depot. Dozens of Marines were sitting around waiting, eating, or playing cards. A hand painted sign of the wall read, &quot;No Loitering.&quot; Many of the long wooden benches held a number of seabags and some Marines were laid out on some benches sound asleep.<br>
              Late that afternoon I was standing next to a water buffalo (a large, round metal container used for the storage of water) with Baracki, Benevedo, and Bennett. They had just met and made friends with a Marine from Camp Lejeune, S.C. who had been assigned to the 3rd Marine  Division. We were talking about what he could expect there, when a Marine came up to me and handed me a handful of MPC.  <br>
He was a Lance Corporal wearing a wrinkled old khaki uniform. His hat cover was missing its Marine  Corps eagle and anchor emblem, and his shoes were old, unpolished and missing their shoe laces. <br>
&quot;Keep yah ass down, keep yah mouth shut, lissen to the old timers, don't volunteer for nuthin; an' in thirteen months you'll leave here in one piece,&quot; he said with a southern drawl, as he handed me the funny looking money along with about 15 South Vietnamese paper dollars in various denominations. The South Vietnamese currency was the piastre, and the official exchange rate was 118 piastres to each U.S. dollar. He had handed me about twelve U.S. dollars worth. <br>
&quot;Ahm on mah way home, an' I ain't got no time ta change this,&quot; he said, as he turned around and walked agilely away.  He had a slight limp and this added to the admiration he was receiving from us, new boots.  I last caught a glimpse of him as he turned the corner and walked toward the out going flights barrack.<br>
                &quot;He made it through Nam, and is now homeward bound, I can make it too,&quot; I said to myself.<br><br>

